column4: The care team conducted a thorough medical history and elicited which medications the patient is currently on.
column5: The care team confirmed that patient has inhaler at the dental appointment
column6: The care team made today’s procedures clear to the patient
column7: The care team established that the patient is doing worse today than in the past (COPD exacerbation).
column8: The care team actively invited input from the team about the current event to provide information and share ideas.
column9: The care team verbalized uncertainty and invited all members to share information and ideas.
column10: The care team formulated a working hypothesis about the patient’s breathing problems.
column11: The care team asked for additional clinical signs and symptoms including “pursed lip breathing” and tripod position of patient.
column12: The care team discussed significance of pitting edema and possibility of cor pulmonale in this setting.
column13: The care team explained their reasoning why something is more important than something else or provided rationale why a specific action needs to be done (e.g., temperature is normal which suggests that an infection is not the cause of the exacerbation).
column14: The care team suggested interventions on managing the patient’s respiratory distress including use of Albuterol inhaler.
column15: The care team made a timely decision to stop or continue with dental treatment.
column16: The care team encouraged smoking cessation—nicotine replacement.
